d into memory. These anti-slavery passions shaped racist and imperialist prejudices, new forms of coerced labor, and the expansion of colonial possessions.In a sweeping narrative that spans the globe, Freedom Burning explores the intersection of philanthropic, imperial, and economic interests that underlay Britain's anti-slavery zeal— from London to Liberia, the Sudan to South Africa, Canada to the Caribbean, and the British East India Company to the Confederate States of America. Through careful attention to popular culture, official records, and private papers, Huzzey rewrites the history of the British Empire and a century-long effort to end the global trade in human lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAbolitionistszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxPublic opinionxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and culturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic opinionzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlave tradezGreat BritainxPublic opinionxHistoryy19th century. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aHistory. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aanti-slavery politics and culture in victorian Britain, queen victoria and anti-slavery, slavery abolition act, when did Britain abolish slavery, role of british anti-slavery politics in the foreign office.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146581940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465819/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL